abstract = {Criteria are developed to evaluate recent theories of roll-call voting in the House of Representatives. Since tests of these very different theories find high levels of pre-dictive success, we must decide how to choose among them. Baseline models are developed to show the extent to which the votes could be predicted with minimal information. The 80-90 percent of the individual votes correctly predicted by the theories is found to be little improvement over the baseline models predicting voting along with the House or party majority. Since the statistical criterion is found to be indeterminate, the importance of verisimilitude to the process being studied is stressed. Simulation studies have done a good job of portraying the process aspects, and they could be usefully combined with statistical studies of long-term forces and interview-ing studies of short-term forces affecting the voting. Theory development in the field should move to a more longitudinal perspective, as well as combining the long-term and short-term elements into a single overarching theory. Several theories of roll-call voting in the U.S. House of Representa-tives have been suggested in recent years. Particularly noteworthy are the simulations by Matthews and Stimson (1975) and by Cherryholmes and Shapiro (1969), the roll-call analysis by Clausen (1973), and the interview study by Kingdon (1973). Since each of these theories has been successfully tested by its author(s), we are faced with significant ques-tions regarding the choice among competing theories. This article is a review essay of these studies, but set within the context of how one should evaluate such theories. The first section considers some of the philosophical issues involved. The second section develops baseline models against which the success of these theories can be measured. The third section critically evaluates the four studies in terms of the criteria and baselines developed in the previous sections. Finally, this paper will examine how a model of legis-lative behavior should be constructed. Each of the existing theories high-lights part of a process, and these parts will be assembled to spotlight more of the process. Criteria for Evaluating Theories The standard statistical criterion for testing a theory involves pre-dicting the dependent behavior on the basis of the independent variables,},
